# Prettier Formatting Rules

This project uses prettier with the following config (`backend/.prettierrc`):
- `singleQuote: true`
- `trailingComma: "all"`

Always apply these rules when writing or editing code.

## Trailing Commas

Add a trailing comma after the last item in multi-line objects, arrays, function arguments, and destructuring.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
await useCase.execute({
  email: 'test@example.com',
  password: 'wrong-password'
});

// ✅ GOOD
await useCase.execute({
  email: 'test@example.com',
  password: 'wrong-password',
});
```

## Multi-line Formatting

When an object or function call has **2 or more properties/arguments**, put each on its own line with a trailing comma. Never keep multiple properties inline.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — multiple properties inline
expect(fn).toHaveBeenCalledWith({ sub: 1, email: 'test@example.com' });
const user = { email: 'a@b.com', name: 'Test', password: 'pass' };
await useCase.execute({ email: 'a@b.com', password: 'pass' });

// ✅ GOOD — each property on its own line
expect(fn).toHaveBeenCalledWith({
  sub: 1,
  email: 'test@example.com',
});
const user = {
  email: 'a@b.com',
  name: 'Test',
  password: 'pass',
};
await useCase.execute({
  email: 'a@b.com',
  password: 'pass',
});
```

Single-property objects may stay inline:

```typescript
// ✅ OK — single property
await repo.findById({ id: 1 });
```

## Single Quotes

Always use single quotes for strings, except when the string itself contains a single quote.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const name = "Test User";

// ✅ GOOD
const name = 'Test User';
```
